data.name: DataBindingList_aspx_litDescription_Text
data.value:
In order to properly bind your chart to a data source, data binding "meta" data about every connection must be kept in memory. This meta data is information that defines how your data source's data columns are to be bound to your chart elements. The list below allows you to view all existing data bindings, and will also allow you to add new data bindings, and edit or delete existing data bindings.

If your chart does not currently have any existing data bindings, but is nevertheless connected to data, it will attempt to render a default view of the data source used. However, it should be noted that in this case the rendered result will be less predictable than using an explicit data binding. You should try to use an explicit data binding where possible.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Numeric_Hint
data.value: Please select one of the numeric formats below

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_General_Hint
data.value: The number is converted to the most compact decimal form, using fixed or scientific notation. The precision specifier determines the number of significant digits in the resulting string.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Currency_Hint
data.value: The number is converted to a string that represents a currency amount. The conversion is controlled by the system currency format information. The precision specifier indicates the desired number of decimal places.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Number_Hint
data.value: The number is converted to a string of the form "-d,ddd,ddd.ddd", where each "d" indicates a digit (0-9). The string starts with a minus sign if the number is negative. Thousand separators are inserted between each group of three digits to the left of the decimal point. The precision specifier indicates the desired number of decimal places.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_FixedPoint_Hint
data.value: The number is converted to a string of the form " -ddd.ddd " where each " d " indicates a digit (0-9). The string starts with a minus sign if the number is negative. The precision specifier indicates the desired number of decimal places.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Percent_Hint
data.value: When using percentages, no actual conversion of any number takes place. Therefore, the precision displayed will always show two decimal places regardless of input. In the example shown here, a percentage sign (%) was simply appended to the original number to indicate that it represents a percentage value.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Scientific_Hint
data.value: The number is converted to a string of the form "-d.dddE+ddd" or " -d.ddde+ddd " , where each "d" indicates a digit (0-9). The string starts with a minus sign if the number is negative. One digit always precedes the decimal point. The precision specifier indicates the desired number of digits after the decimal point.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_DateTime_Hint
data.value: Please select one of the numeric formats below

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_ShortDate_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the short date format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_LongDate_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the long date format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_ShortTime_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the short time format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_LongTime_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the long time format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_FullShortTime_Hint
data.value: Displays a combination of the long date and short time patterns, separated by a space.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_FullLongTime_Hint
data.value: Displays a combination of the long date and long time patterns, separated by a space.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_GeneralShortTime_Hint
data.value: Displays a combination of the short date and short time patterns, separated by a space.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_GeneralLongTime_Hint
data.value: Displays a combination of the short date and long time patterns, separated by a space.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_MonthDay_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the month day format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_RFC_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the RFC1123 standart format. It follows the custom pattern "ddd, dd MMMM yyyy HH:mm:ss G\MT". Note that the "M" in "GMT" needs an escape character so it is not interpreted.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_ISO_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the sortable format. Format follows the custom pattern "yyyy-MM-ddTHH:mm:ss".

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_UniversalSortable_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the universal sortable format. Pattern is always the same regardless of culture or format provider. The format follows the custom pattern "yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ssZ".

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_UniversalFull_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the universal full format. Pattern is always the same regardless of culture or format provider. Note that the time displayed is for the Universal, rather than local time.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_YearMonth_Hint
data.value: The date/time is converted to the year month format.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_Custom_Hint
data.value: Pick one of the custom formats

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_CustomNumeric_Hint
data.value: Characters that can be used to create custom numeric format strings: "0" - Zero placeholder, "#" - Digit placeholder, "." - Decimal point, "," - Thousand separator and number scaling, "%" - Percentage placeholder, "E0" - Scientific notation, "\" - Escape character, ";" - Section separator. All other characters are copied to the output string as literals in the position they appear.

data.name: FormatPickerDialog_aspx_Type_CustomDateTime_Hint
data.value: Some characters that can be used to create custom date/time format strings: "d or dd" - One or two digit day of the month, "ddd or dddd" - Three character or full week day name, "h or hh" - One or two digit hour (1-12), "H or HH" - One or two digit hour (1-24), "m or mm" - One or two digit minute, "M or MM" - One or two digit month, "MMM or MMMM" - Three character or full month name, "s or ss" - One or two digit second, "t or tt" - One or full A.M./P.M. designator, "y or yy or yyy" - One, two digit or full year.
